  "prompt": "What is the oxidation number of nitrogen?",
  "response": "The oxidation number of nitrogen can vary depending on the compound it is in. Here are some common oxidation states of nitrogen:\n\n1. **Nitrogen (N\u2082)**: In its elemental form, the oxidation number of nitrogen is **0**.\n2. **Ammonia (NH\u2083)**: In ammonia, nitrogen has an oxidation number of **-3**.\n3. **Nitric oxide (NO)**: In nitric oxide, nitrogen has an oxidation number of **+2**.\n4. **Nitrogen dioxide (NO\u2082)**: In nitrogen dioxide, nitrogen has an oxidation number of **+4**.\n5. **Nitrate ion (NO\u2083\u207b)**: In the nitrate ion, nitrogen has an oxidation number of **+5**.\n6. **Nitrite ion (NO\u2082\u207b)**: In the nitrite ion, nitrogen has an oxidation number of **+3**.\n\nThese are just a few examples. Nitrogen can exhibit a wide range of oxidation numbers depending on the specific compound and its bonding environment.",
